---
import SiteLayout from '../layouts/SiteLayout.astro';
---

<SiteLayout
	title="About Dean Tool"
	description="Learn the story behind Dean Tool's dark lounge sound and stage persona."
	active="about"
>
	<section class="section">
		<div class="story-grid">
			<article class="bio-card">
				<span class="eyebrow">The Story</span>
				<h1 class="display-title">A voice built for velvet rooms and dangerous timing.</h1>
				<p class="muted">
					Born Dino Teodoro Tullio to Italian immigrant parents who landed in Newark with two suitcases,
					a saint card, and a recipe book wrapped in butcher paper, Dean Tool grew up above a family
					butcher shop where opera records, church choirs, and whispered neighborhood business all mixed
					in the same thin-walled rooms. By sixteen he could trim a side of beef, memorize a room full
					of favors, and hold a note long enough to stop an argument cold.
				</p>
				<p class="muted">
					In the years that followed, Dean drifted from social clubs to supper rooms and, depending on
					which version of the story you believe, spent a short but unforgettable stretch doing quiet
					work for men who preferred cash, loyalty, and dark sedans. When a last-minute singer failed to
					show at the Starlite Palms in Atlantic City, Dean took the stage in a borrowed tuxedo, sang
					three torch songs and a Neapolitan standard, and walked off with a standing ovation, a record
					offer, and half the city insisting they had discovered him first.
				</p>
				<p class="muted">
					From there the legend only widened: sold-out showroom runs, midnight orchestras, tabloid
					headlines, and a catalog of velvet-heavy records that made danger sound expensive. Through all
					of it, Dean Tool kept the same code he claimed to learn at home: dress sharp, speak softly,
					never waste a spotlight, and leave the room with people wondering what really happened.
				</p>
			</article>
			<aside class="quote-card">
				<span class="eyebrow">Artist Statement</span>
				<blockquote>"If the room remembers the suit before the song, you did the song wrong."</blockquote>
				<p>
					That code still shapes the act: old-country pride, showroom polish, and just enough danger to
					make the brass section sound sharper.
				</p>
			</aside>
		</div>
	</section>

	<section class="section">
		<div class="section-panel">
			<div class="section-heading">
				<div>
					<span class="eyebrow">What Defines The Sound</span>
					<h2 class="section-title">Classic craft with a modern silhouette.</h2>
				</div>
			</div>
			<div class="stats-grid">
				<div class="stat-card">
					<strong>Old World</strong>
					<span>Family legends, immigrant grit, and neighborhood codes stitched into the persona.</span>
				</div>
				<div class="stat-card">
					<strong>Showroom</strong>
					<span>Big-band luxury, immaculate tailoring, and entrances timed like theater.</span>
				</div>
				<div class="stat-card">
					<strong>Underworld</strong>
					<span>Rumor, shadow, and the sense that every great song has a back-room story behind it.</span>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>
	</section>
</SiteLayout>
